					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Context switches are expensive; when one uses coroutines there's much less state to save and restore. I'd be worried about the overhead overwhelming the benefits...</div><br />Good point, one would have to have a full copy of all cpu registers at the time a thread is pre-empted, whereas with coroutines all I need is the state associated with the coroutine (in my game's case, just the current entity's state)...(and the PC)<br /><br />Given that, I'm guessing any time I've seen the word &quot;thread&quot; used in an NES game's source code, it is probably really a coroutine or similar idea...</div>

